","Shelford, Nottinghamshire, England":"Shelford, Nottinghamshire, England","Tuxford, Nottinghamshire, England":"Tuxford, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"1170–1220":"1170–1220","1165–1250":"1165–1250","1185–Male":"1185–Overleden","1187–1238":"1187–1238","1187–1257":"1187–1257","1190–1250":"1190–1250","1195–1240":"1195–1240","1196–1258":"1196–1258","1198–1258":"1198–1258","1190":"1190","1187":"1187","1220":"1220","1198":"1198","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","1196":"1196","1240":"1240","1195":"1195","1250":"1250","1170":"1170","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1258":"1258","1257":"1257","about 1187":"circa 1187","about 1198":"circa 1198","about 1196":"circa 1196","Warsop, Nottinghamshire, England":"Warsop, Nottinghamshire, England","Tuxford, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Tuxford, Nottinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Shelford, Nottinghamshire, England":"Shelford, Nottinghamshire, England","Tuxford, Nottinghamshire, England":"Tuxford, Nottinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1170–1220":"1170–1220","1165–1250":"1165–1250","1185–Male":"1185–Deceased","1187–1238":"1187–1238","1187–1257":"1187–1257","1190–1250":"1190–1250","1195–1240":"1195–1240","1196–1258":"1196–1258","1198–1258":"1198–1258","1190":"1190","1187":"1187","1220":"1220","1198":"1198","1165":"1165","1185":"1185","1196":"1196","1240":"1240","1195":"1195","1250":"1250","1170":"1170","1238":"1238","1215":"1215","1258":"1258","1257":"1257","about 1187":"about 1187","about 1198":"about 1198","about 1196":"about 1196","Warsop, Nottinghamshire, England":"Warsop, Nottinghamshire, England","Tuxford, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Tuxford, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Shelford, Nottinghamshire, England":"Shelford, Nottinghamshire, England","Tuxford, Nottinghamshire, England":"Tuxford, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Matilda","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized form of a Germanic personal name derived from <i>maht</i>, <i>meht</i> ‘might’ + <i>hild</i> ‘battle’. This was the name of an early German queen (  895–968 ), wife of  Henry  the Fowler, who was noted for her piety and generosity. It was also the name of the wife of  William  the Conqueror and of the daughter of  Henry I  of England (  see  Maud  ). The name was introduced into England by the Normans, and this Latinized form is the one that normally occurs in medieval records, while the vernacular form <i>Maud</i> was the one in everyday use. <i>Matilda</i> was revived in England as a learned form in the 18th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathilda","meanings":["Old German: Mighty battle maid"]}]},{"name":"of","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Oswald   or any of the various other names beginning with <i>Os-</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Sherwood","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called with Old English <i>scīr</i> + <i>wudu</i> ‘bright or clear (perhaps sparsely-grown) wood’. In Yorkshire the name usually refers to Sherwood (Hall) in Eggborough (Yorkshire), but some examples could alternatively derive from Sherwood (House) in Stainforth (Yorkshire) or from the Nottinghamshire forest name in 2 below. The Devon name is from Sherwood (Green) in Yarnscombe (Devon). These are well evidenced as medieval placenames, and there may be similar but unrecorded places that could account for the medieval surname in other counties such as East Yorkshire, Norfolk, Oxfordshire, and Sussex. <i>Sherwood</i> occurs in minor placenames in Berkshire, Hampshire, Hertfordshire, Kent, North Yorkshire, Sussex, and Wiltshire, but they are recorded only in modern times and in many cases will have been named from the surname or perhaps in imitation of 2 below. This name was established in Ireland in the 17th century. See also   Sherrard  .","English: habitational name from Sherwood Forest in Nottinghamshire (‘the shire wood’).","Americanized form of some Jewish name."],"variants":[{"name":"Sherrard","meanings":["English:","from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Shirard</i> (Old English <i>Scīrheard</i>, composed of the elements <i>scīr</i> ‘bright’ and <i>heard</i> ‘hard, bold’). Alternatively, the name may be a nickname deriving from Middle English <i>shir</i> (Old English <i>scīr</i>) ‘bright, fair’, with the addition of the Anglo-Norman French suffix <i>-ard</i>.","local pronunciation of   Sherwood  , especially perhaps in Leicestershire, Kent, Lincolnshire, Norfolk, Sussex, and Yorkshire. It may also have been much confused with   Skerritt  . This name, or the name in 1 above, has been established in Ireland (Derry) since the 17th century, along with <i>Sherwood</i> (in most provinces)."]}]},{"name":"Forest","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: transferred use of the surname, in origin a local name for someone who lived in or by an enclosed wood, Old French <i>forest</i>."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":45,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Matilda of Sherwood Forest was born in 1170, in Shelford, Nottinghamshire, England. Sh